{{pagebanner|Paris 5e Wikivoyage Banner.png|pgname=5th arrondissement}} The '''[http://www.paris5eme.com/indexag.htm 5th Arrondissement]''' of Paris is one of the best known of the city's central districts, located on the Left Bank (''Rive Gauche'') of the river Seine. Also commonly known as the "Latin Quarter" (''le Quartier latin'') because the first great Parisian university, the Sorbonne, was founded (and can be still be found) here and Latin was the language the medieval period students used once to speak. The 5th was also the core of ancient Gallo-Roman Paris, as revealed in a number of otherwise rare archaeological remains that can be seen within the district.
The area still has a significant student presence, with several universities and schools of higher education being located in the area. However, due to gentrification, most student and faculty have been forced to more affordable areas such as the [[Paris/13th arrondissement|13th]].
==Get in== [[Image:Paris 5th pantheon.jpg|thumb|250px|The Panthéon crowns the hill at the center of Paris' 5th arrondissement]] ===''By Métro''===
{{rint|paris|7}} connects the 5th with the 1st, 4th, and 13th, stopping at '''Jussieu''', '''Monge''' and '''Censier/Daubenton'''.
{{rint|paris|10}} cuts east-west across the northern and most touristed part of the arrondissement stopping at '''Cluny/la Sorbonne''', '''Maubert/Mutualité''', '''Cardinal Lemoine''', and '''Jussieu''' with terminus just east of the 5th's border with the 13th at '''Gare d'Austerlitz'''.
{{rint|paris|rerB}} coming all the way from '''[[Charles de Gaulle Airport]]''' stops at '''St. Michel''' and '''Luxembourg'''.
===''By bus''=== 27, 87, 86, 24, 21, 47, 89, 84
Many tourists rely on the subway system to get around. However, while you are there to visit, why not see the city from the bus? Unlike other big cities, the buses in Paris are a first class ride for the same price. They are very clean and usually arrive every 7-10 minutes. The system is very easy to understand (there are big maps and the lines are color coded) and you can ask anyone on the bus to tell you where you should stop. Buses typically go faster than other cars too because they benefit from special '''bus lanes''' on all main avenues and boulevards throughout the city.
==See== {{Mapframe|48.84513|2.35017|zoom=14|staticmap=Paris 5th arrondissement map with listings 2.png}} {{Mapshape}} {{Mapshapes|Q50716}}
===Landmarks=== * {{see | name=Panthéon | alt= | url=http://pantheon.monuments-nationaux.fr/fr/ | email= | address=Place du Panthéon | lat=48.846111 | long=2.345833 | directions={{station|Cardinal Lemoine|10}} or {{station|Luxembourg|rerB}} | phone=+33 1 43 54 34 51 | tollfree= | hours=Daily, April-September 10:00-18:30, October-March: 10:00-18:00, Last admission 45 mins before closing | price=€7.50 (''€4.50 reduced rate, museum card accepted, free for EU-people under 26 years, incl Panorama Tower, but needs to be explicitly asked for'') | wikipedia=Panthéon | image=Panthéon Paris 2.jpg | wikidata=Q188856 | content=It was conceived by Louis XV as a grand neo-classical church honouring St. Geneviève, the patron saint of Paris. After the Revolution, the building was converted into a mausoleum for the great philosophers, military, artists, scientists, and heroes of the French Republic. Occupants of the crypt include Voltaire, Rousseau, Victor Hugo, Zola, the Curies, and Alexandre Dumas (reinterred here in 2002). The view from the dome (206 steps) is marvellous. Check tour departure times at the information desk. A fascinating reconstruction of Foucault's pendulum also hangs within the Panthéon. }} * {{see | name=Jardin des Plantes | alt= | url=http://www.mnhn.fr/museum/foffice/tous/tous/GuideDecouverte/lieuxVisiter/LieuxAVisiter/FLieuAVisiter.xsp?AE_ID214&INFO_ID21&LIEU_ID158&MAN_ID273&SITE_ID10&idx1&navliste | email= | address= | lat=48.843889 | long=2.359722 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours=daily summer 07:30 - 20:00, winter 8:00 - 17:30 | price=free | wikipedia=Jardin des Plantes | image=Jardin Plantes.jpg | wikidata=Q730948 | content=The Paris Botanical Garden, founded as the royal medicinal garden in 1626 by King Louis XIII's doctor, contains over 10,000 species. The grounds also include a small zoo known as ''La Ménagerie'', and the '''Muséum National d'Histoire Naturelle''', which includes the ''Grande Galerie de l'Evolution'' (where you can see thousands of naturalized animals from all over the world) and the ''''Galerie de paléontologie et d'anatomie comparée'''' (same thing, but with skeletons). }} * {{see | name=Arènes de Lutèce | alt= | url= | email= | address=47, rue Monge et rue de Navarre | lat=48.845 | long=2.35306 | directions={{station|Place Monge}}, {{station|Jussieu}}, {{station|Cardinal Lemoine}} | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours=08ː00-17ː30 (winter), 08ː00-22ː00 (summer) | price=Free | wikipedia=Arènes de Lutèce | image=Roman arena in Paris.jpg | wikidata=Q641548 | content=An ancient Roman theater, the only surviving above-ground ruins of the Gallo-Roman era in Paris (ancient Lutetia, French ''Lutèce'') apart from the nearby ''Thermes de Cluny''. The theatre could hold approximately 15,000 spectators and measures some 132 m x 100 m. Built sometime in the 2nd century CE, the location of the actor's dressing room, the platform of the stage, and lapidary remains can still be seen. The remains were rediscovered in 1869, when new streets were being built. An excavation was subsequently ordered in 1883. The theatre has been preserved as a quiet archaeological park removed from the bustle of Parisian streets. }}
[[File:Façade de la chapelle Sainte-Ursule, Sorbonne, Paris.jpg|thumb|Façade of the Chapel Sainte-Ursule of the Sorbonne]]
===Museums and Galleries=== * {{see | name=Musée Curie | alt= | url=http://musee.curie.fr/ | email= | address=11, rue Pierre et Marie Curie | lat=48.844167 | long=2.343611 | directions={{station|Cardinal Lemoine|10}}, {{station|Place Monge|7}}, {{station|Luxembourg|rerB}} | phone=+33 1 42 34 67 49 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=M-F 13ː30-17ː00 except bank holidays and during Aug | price=free | wikipedia=Musée Curie | image=Entrance to Musee Curie, Paris.jpg | wikidata=Q589336 | content=This charming scientific museum preserves the offices and laboratories of Pierre and Marie Curie, pioneers in the discovery of radioactivity. Their instruments, equipment, and furniture is arranged as it was during their critically important research. Guided tours in English available. }} * {{see | name=Musée de l'Institut du Monde Arabe | alt=Arab World Institute | url=http://www.imarabe.org/ | email= | address=1, rue des Fossés-St Bernard | lat=48.84889 | long=2.35639 | directions= | phone=+33 1 40 51 38 38 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=Tu-Su 10ː00-18ː00, closed M and 1 May | price= | wikipedia=Arab World Institute | image=Osiris, mystères engloutis d'Égypte, Institut du Monde Arabe, Paris 24 January 2016.jpg | wikidata=Q860166 | content=The building has a freely accessible rooftop which allows for a beautiful bird's-eye view of the northern half of Paris. }} * {{see | name=Musée National Du Moyen Âge | alt=Musée de Cluny | url=http://www.musee-moyenage.fr/ | email= | address=6, place Paul Painlevé | lat=48.850556 | long=2.343333 | directions={{station|Cluny-La Sorbonne|10}} | phone=+33 1 53 73 78 16 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=Daily 09:15-17:15 | price=€7.50 (€5.50 reduced rate, free under 18, museum card accepted) | wikipedia=Musée national du Moyen Âge | image=Hotel de cluny entrance.jpg | wikidata=Q1124095 | lastedit=2017-02-06 | content=Housed in a 15th-century abbey, alongside 1st century Gallo-Roman baths, the museum has an extensive collection of medieval art and artifacts. Highlights include the medieval "Lady and the Unicorn" tapestries, a papal golden rose, and the original heads from the facade of Notre Dame. }}
===Religious buildings=== * {{see | name=Eglise Saint-Étienne-du-Mont | alt= | url=http://www.saintetiennedumont.fr/ | email= | address=pl Ste Geneviève | lat=48.846389 | long=2.347778 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | wikipedia=Saint-Étienne-du-Mont | image=Saint-Étienne-du-Mont3.JPG | wikidata=Q583251 | content=St. Geneviève was responsible for saving Paris from the Huns in 451 and her shrine in the church has been a popular place of pilgrimage ever since. The church as it stands dates from between 1492 and 1626 and is a mix of Gothic and Renaissance architectural styles. A unique feature is the Renaissance rood screen, the sole survivor in the city. }} * {{see | name=Eglise Saint-Julien-le-Pauvre | alt= | url= | email= | address=rue Saint-Julien-le-Pauvre | lat=48.851944 | long=2.346944 | directions={{station|Cluny-Sorbonne}} / {{station|Saint-Michel}} | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | wikipedia=Saint-Julien-le-Pauvre | image=Saint Julien le Pauvre 02.jpg | wikidata=Q1243760 | content= }} *{{see | name=Eglise Saint-Médard | alt= | url=http://saintmedard.org | email= | address=rue Mouffetard | lat=48.83992 | long=2.350484 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | wikipedia=fr:Église Saint-Médard de Paris | image=Paris 5e - église Saint-Médard - ext 1.JPG | wikidata=Q574970 | content= }} * {{see | name=Eglise Saint Nicolas du Chardonnet | alt= | url=http://www.saintnicolasduchardonnet.fr/ | email= | address=23, rue des Bernardins | lat=48.849167 | long=2.350278 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | wikipedia=Saint-Nicolas-du-Chardonnet | image=3-4view Saint-Nicolas-du-Chardonnet Paris.jpg | wikidata=Q1577630 | content=A controversial church serving as de facto headquarters of the arch-traditionalist Society of Saint Pius X, who occupied the church in 1977 and have ignored subsequent eviction orders. }} * {{see | name=Grande Mosquée de Paris | alt=Grand Mosque of Paris | url=http://www.mosqueedeparis.net | email= | address=2 bis, place du puits de l'Ermite | lat=48.841944 | long=2.355 | directions= | phone=+33 1 45 35 97 33 | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | wikipedia=Grand Mosque of Paris | image=GD-FR-Paris-Mosquée012.JPG | wikidata=Q392564 | content=Established in 1926, it was meant to show appreciation for Muslim help in fighting the Germans. The café serves excellent mint tea and North African food. }} * {{see | name=Église Saint-Jacques-du-Haut-Pas | alt= | url=http://www.saintjacquesduhautpas.com/ | email= | address= | lat=48.843611 | long=2.341389 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | wikipedia=Église Saint-Jacques-du-Haut-Pas | image=P1010463 Paris V Saint-Jacques-du-Haut-Pas reductwk.JPG | wikidata=Q65326 | lastedit=2017-06-24 | content= }}
==Do== The 5th arrondissement is the perfect place to wander and people watch. If you are brave and have any French skills, engage a student in conversation. Many, if addressed in French, will be more than happy to talk about politics and social issues in English.
==Buy== [[File:Rue Mouffetard.JPG|thumb|250px|The rue Mouffetard hosts an ongoing open air market]]
The lower end of rue Mouffetard as it runs away from the ''Panthéon'' hosts an ongoing fruit and vegetable market, and is lined with food and wine shops of all kinds.
* {{buy | name=l'Epée de Bois | url= | email= | address=12, rue de l'Epée de Bois | lat=48.84160 | long=2.35023 | directions=Métro: Pl. Monge | phone=+33 1 43 31 50 18 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=M 13:30-19:30; Tu-Sa 10:30-19:30; Su 11:00-13:30 | price= | content=The name of the store and the street it's on both translate to the "wooden sword", and you find those here along with any number of wooden toys for children ages 1 to 10. They also have books and games.}} * {{buy | name=La Fontaine aux Vins | url= | email= | address=107 rue Mouffetard | lat=48.84075 | long=2.34980 | directions=Métro: Censier Daubenton | phone=+33 1 43 31 41 03 | tollfree= | fax=+33 1 45 34 51 47 | hours= | price= | content=One of several wine shops along the lower part of the street. The wines are of high quality, but barely more pricey than the ones you'll find in the grocery store. They offer tastings outside on the street, and delivery if you buy a case. Prices start at around €4 per bottle which is around what you'll pay for a glass in a bar.}} * {{buy | name=Gepetto & Vélos | url= | email= | address=46, rue Daubenton | lat=48.84021 | long=2.35023 | directions=Métro: Censier Daubenton | phone=+33 1 43 37 16 17 | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | content=OK, so if you are just staying for a day or two it makes no sense whatever to buy a bike, but if you are going to be around for a while having your own might just feel better than renting one from the RATP. If so, you could do a lot worse than Gepetto, where you'll find a range of real bikes rather than the usual cheap MTB you'd see at a sporting goods store. Prices start at around €100 for a sturdy used, 3-speed city bike.}} * {{buy | name=Shakespeare and Co. | url=http://www.shakespeareandcompany.com/ | email= | address=37, rue de la Bûcherie | lat=48.85255 | long=2.34709 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours=Daily 12ː00-24ː00 | price=Cash only | content=Probably one of the most eccentric bookstores you will ever visit, this must-see was established in 1951 by George Whitman. Three rambling floors literally crammed with books, both new and (mainly) second-hand. The bedding shoved amid the shelves is for the (largely American) expats (called tumbleweeds) who doss down here at night. It is the sister store to City Lights in San Francisco.}}
==Eat== {{eatpricerange|below €15|€15-25|over €25|dinner typical set menu (starter+main+dessert whenever available)}}
A lot of travellers arriving in the 5th from across the river are lured into the restaurants and fast-food outlets between rue St Jacques and boulevard St Michel (in Rue de la Huchette, rue Saint-Séverin). This area may be handy for a quick snack (say, a "Greek sandwich" in a pita), but the quality of restaurants there is not so good - beware especially of restaurants advertising typical French specialties. A similar phenomenon occurs around rue Mouffetard, where many students from the Jussieu Campus and the École normale supérieure have snacks; most of the "French" restaurants are overpriced tourist traps.
===Budget=== * {{eat | name=Le Grenier de Notre Dame | url= | email= | address=18, rue de la Bûcherie | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: St. Michel | phone=+33 1 43 29 98 29 | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price=Dinners start at €12 | content=A vegetarian restaurant with a great selection including a number of vegan items, the Grenier is, as the name suggests, just around the corner from the cathedral. The English-speaking staff is super friendly.}} * {{eat | name=Jardin des Pâtes | url= | email= | address=4, rue Lacépède | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Monge | phone=+33 1 43 31 50 71 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=Daily 12ː00-14:30 and 19ː00-23ː00 | price=Menus around €12 | content=The range of pasta dishes is just fantastic at this cute little restaurant tucked away near the ''Jardin des Plantes''. Although some meat dishes are served there is a huge range of choice for vegetarians as well.}}
===Mid-range=== * {{eat | name=Ambiance De L'Inde | url=http://www.ambiancedelinde.com {{dead link|June 2020|December 2020}} | email=battish@gmail.com | address=12, rue Thouin | lat= | long= | directions= | phone=+33 1 40 46 03 76 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=Daily | price= | content=Indian/Pakistani with many vegan dishes.}} * {{eat | name=Chez Ernest | url= | email= | address=31, rue de la Parcheminerie | lat= | long= | directions=Métro Cluny-Sorbonne | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price=Complete dinner, including beverages, for €25 | content=Very nice little restaurant in a small side-street. Typical and less typical French food.}} *{{eat | name=Kootchi | url= | email= | address=40, rue du Cardinal Lemoine | lat= | long= | directions=Métro Cardinal Lemoine | phone = +33 1 44 07 20 56 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=M-Sa 12ː00-14:30, 19ː00-22:30 | price=Lunch menu: €9.20 or €12.20, dinner menu €15.50 | content=Afghan cuisine, small and cosy, food is not too spicy, good value for money.}} * {{eat | name=Le Petit Prince de Paris | alt= | url=http://lepetitprincedeparis.fr/ | email= | address=12, rue de Lanneau | lat=48.848421 | long=2.34653 | directions=Métro 10 Maubert-Mutualité, close to Pantheon | phone=+33 1 43 54 77 26 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=Evenings 19:30-24ː00 (to 00:30 F-Sa) | price=Set menu (starter+main) €16-23; extra €6 for dessert | content=A notably Parisian restaurant experience, but with friendly and warm service. Traditional French food (try the duck with feathers) and deliciously complicated sauces. Relaxed and uncrowded, but reserve in the morning for a weekend night. Reasonable wine selection.}} *{{eat | name=Le Volcan | url=http://www.restaurant-levolcan.fr/ {{dead link|June 2020|December 2020}} | email= | address=10, rue Thouin | lat= | long= | directions=Near rue Descartes | phone=+33 1 46 33 38 33 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=Tu-Su 12ː00-23ː00 | price=€25 per person without wine | content=Serves delicious traditional French dishes in a welcoming environment. Excellent service. The set meals are very varied and represent superb value.}}
===Splurge=== *{{eat | name=Bibimpap | url=http://www.bibimbap.fr | email= | address=32, boul de l'Hôpital | lat= | long= | directions=Métro Gare d'Austerlitz | phone = +33 1 43312742 | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price=Set menu €25-40 | content=Korean restaurant.}} *{{eat | name=Coco de Mer | url=http://www.cocodemer.fr | email= | address=34, boul St Marcel | lat= | long= | directions=Métro St Marcel | phone = +33 1 47070664 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=Closed M lunch, Su, 2 weeks in Aug | price=Set menu €30, à la carte from €28-36 | content=Specialities from the Seychelles.}} * {{eat | name=Dans les Landes | alt= | url=http://www.dansleslandesmaisaparis.com/ {{dead link|August 2018|December 2020}} | email=dansleslandes@hotmail.fr | address=119 bis, rue Monge | lat=48.839069 | long=2.351036 | directions=Censier-Daubenton | phone=+33 1 45 87 06 00 | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | content=A tapas bar with food from southeast France is the new place of the rugby champion and chef Julien Duboué.}} * {{eat | name=Le Petit Pontoise | url= | email= | address=9, rue de Pontoise| lat= | long= | directions=Parallel with the separation of lle de la Cite and lle de la Saint-Louis | phone = +33 1 43 29 25 20 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=Open lunch and dinner | price=Main courses for €18-28, starters and desserts €7-11, wine €20+ | content=Nice restaurant with a homey feel, on a quiet street. Popular enough to have an "also" section next door. Expatriate Americans mingle with native Parisians and a few tourists. The food is of the local French standard (i.e., high), but does include vegetables, which many other non-tourist restaurants do not. The balance and spicing of the sauces is the main draw. The pig's cheeks stew is notably delicious, and one of the cheaper items to boot!}} * {{eat | name=La Tour d'Argent | alt= | url=http://www.tourdargent.com/ | email= | address=15-17, quai de la Tournelle | lat= | long= | directions=Métro Cardinal Lemoine or St Paul | phone=+33 1 43 54 23 31 | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | content=For those with fat wallets la Tour d'Argent is a must-do. One of the oldest restaurants in Paris, on the Seine, it is famous for its duck recipes.}}
==Drink== [[File:Jardin Plantes.jpg|thumb|The Museum of Natural History in the Jardin des Plantes]] * {{drink | name=The Bombardier | url= | email= | address=place du Panthéon | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Maubert/Mutualité | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | content=Great pub in a prime location right in front of beautiful St-Etienne-du-Mont church and the Panthéon. One of the few pubs in Paris where you can get cask ales, and they also make cocktails. Food served at lunchtime (good pub food, e.g., bangers & mash, English breakfasts, fish & chips, etc.). Also a great place to watch sporting events like Premier League matches and the Six-Nations tournament as the pub draws a mixed crowd of French and English regulars with expats and tourists thrown into the mix.}} * {{drink | name=The Fifth Bar | url= | email= | address=62, rue Mouffetard | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Place Monge | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price=Lager pints are €3.50 at happy hour, €5 after 20ː00 (except for student nights) | content=Named for the arrondissement, or maybe a measure of whiskey, this little hole-in-the-wall caters to a mixed anglophone expatriate crowd, with a mix of local students and (in tourist season) backpackers. Tuesdays and Thursdays are student nights with happy-hour prices all night with a student ID. Depending on season, American sports often play on the television, as do English Premier league and Spanish Primera matches.}} * {{drink | name=Le Piano Vache | url= | email= | address=8, Rue Laplace | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Maubert/Mutualité | phone=+33 1 46 33 75 03 | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price=Beer €3.50, mixed drinks €6.50, coffee €1 | content=A legendary part of student life in the real Latin quarter this dark barroom has walls covered with posters and photos of bands, but also a wall covered with passport-type photos of regulars past and present. At night things get going with DJs, bands of all styles, and on Tuesday nights, a pop-rock jam session.}} * {{drink | name=Polly Magoo | url= | email= | address=3, rue du Petit Pont | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Saint Michel | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours=Su-Th 12ː00-05ː00; F Sa 12ː00-08ː00 | price=''Formule'': (1 tapa, 1 beer) is €8 | content=This bar bears no relation, beyond the name, to the legendary, sleazy, and legendarily sleazy bar which was further south up the street at 11, rue Saint Jacques and was replaced by a boutique hotel in 2002. Jim Morrison was a regular at the original bar, but the owners of the new version would be unlikely to let anyone that shabby come in. The Gaudi-esque bar and blue mosaic storefront make this bar a must see as well as a must sit for those who like their bars to come with a theme.}} * {{drink | name=Le Vieux Chêne | url= | email= | address=69, rue Mouffetard | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Place Monge | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | content=Just down the way from the fifth on the left is another hole-in-the-wall, this one dating from the 18th century. It was named after its sign, a bas relief of an old oak tree (vieux chene), which was around 250 years when it was chiselled off early in 2005 by workmen restoring the facade of the building. The selection of beers, etc., is good and the crowd is mostly students. Expect to pay around €4 for a pint. There is a minuscule dance floor in the atmospheric and sweaty cellar below. On Tuesday nights, there is live music and the musicians take requests from the crowd, playing classic French and American songs.}}
==Sleep== [[File:St-Etienne-du-Mont Exterior, Paris, France - Diliff.jpg|thumb|St. Etienne du Mont in its Renaissance glory, just behind the Panthéon]] ===Budget=== * {{sleep | name=Hôtel du Commerce | url=http://www.commerce-paris-hotel.com | email= | address=14, rue de la Montagne-Sainte-Geneviève | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Maubert-Mutualité | phone=+33 1 43 54 89 69 | tollfree= | fax=+33 1 43 54 76 09 | hours= | price=Singles without start at €26. Showers cost €2 | checkin= | checkout= | content=The rooms are tiny, but cheap, especially for the location, just a stone's throw from Notre Dame. The hotel provides a shared kitchen area if you would like to save even more money by cooking some of the time, there are markets both nearby and over the hill on rue Mouffetard, so this is a good idea for budget travellers. Although they do have exactly one (pricier) room equipped with a shower, the rest of the rooms share a brand-new shower near the reception.}} * {{sleep | name=Hôtel Esmerelda | url= | email= | address=4, rue Saint-Julien-le-Pauvre | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Saint-Michel | phone=+33 1 43 54 19 20 | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price=A basic room is €65, doubles are €80-95 | checkin= | checkout= | content=An excellent example of what happens when a "find" hotel is discovered by the travel guides, the Esmerelda has lost none of its charm, but the prices have crept up into nearly the two-star range, and you'll have to book ahead by at least a couple of months in the high season or around the winter holidays. On the plus side the place really does deserve the attention (and solid bookings), as it really is super charming, the welcome couldn't possibly be better and it's still on the cheap side. Try not to trip over the ample knick-knacks in your room, which will likely be named after a French singing star.}} * {{sleep | name=Port-Royal-Hôtel | url=http://www.hotelportroyal.fr | email= | address=8, boul de Port-Royal | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Les Gobelins | phone=+33 1 43 31 70 06 | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price=€39-87. Average room rate is around €55. Ask for a room with a bidet. | checkin= | checkout= | content=Great hotel next to the rue Mouffetard and its market. Whimsical rooms decorated in rich floral patterns.}} * {{sleep | name=Young and Happy Hostel | url=http://www.youngandhappy.fr | email= | address=80, rue Mouffetard | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Place Monge | phone=+33 1 47 07 47 07 | tollfree= | fax=+33 1 47 07 22 24 | hours= | price=A dorm-room bed costs €28, while a double goes for €80 | checkin= | checkout= | content=A hit with young travellers, the young and happy exists to save you money. The rooms are just as basic as can be, but clean unlike the average one-star, though they (in theory) turf you out at 11ː00 every morning to get them this clean. The location is hard to beat if you are looking for a nice evening out. The risk though is that if you party too much you won't see much else of [[Paris]]. Oh, English is the lingua-franca here.}}
===Mid-range=== * {{sleep | name=Hotel Cujas Pantheon | url=http://www.cujas-pantheon-paris-hotel.com/ | email=hotel-cujas-pantheon@wanadoo.fr | address=18, rue Cujas | lat= | long= | directions= | phone = +33 1 43 54 58 10 | tollfree= | fax=+33 1 43 25 88 02 | hours= | price=Single €74, double €97 | checkin= | checkout= | content=A small and tidy hotel situated on a quiet side street right beside the Sorbonne University and 5 min walking distance from the nearest métro station (Cluny-La Sorbonne) and the Panthéon.}} * {{sleep | name=Hôtel de l'Esperance | url=http://www.hoteldelesperance.fr | email= | address=15, rue Pascal | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Place Monge or Censier-Daubenton | phone=+33 1 47 07 10 99 | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price=€80-120 | checkin= | checkout= | content=This quirky little little family-run hotel just off of place Contrescarp and the rue Mouffetard has some really good value rooms, especially up on the top floor. The young staff gets high ratings, as does the proprietress (even with her very limited English), though it's sometimes best to avoid the proprietor depending on mood.}} * {{sleep | name=Hôtel Familia | url=http://www.hotel-paris-familia.com | email= | address=11, rue des Ecoles | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Maubert-Mutualité or Cardinal-Lemoine | phone=+33 1 43 54 55 27 | tollfree= | fax=+33 1 43 29 61 77 | hours= | price=€73.50-90 | checkin= | checkout= | content=As with the Minerve (below), each of the rooms in this family run two-star is decorated with a unique medievalist mural by the artist Gérald Pritchard. This, combined with the antique furniture, gives the place some real character. If you are lucky enough to get a room with a balcony (ask!) you can enjoy your breakfast overlooking the courtyard (or the street).}} * {{sleep | name=Hôtel du Levant | url=http://www.hoteldulevant.com/ | email=info@hoteldulevant.com | address=18, rue de la Harpe | lat= | long= | directions=Métro/ RER B Saint-Michel | phone=+33 1 46 34 11 00 | tollfree= | fax=+33 1 46 34 25 87 | hours= | price=€115-150 including breakfast and tax | checkin= | checkout= | content=Scoring consistently high marks for quality and spaciousness the ''du Levant'' is close to ''Place St. Michel''. Apparently the rooms are mostly of a standard Paris size (small) but there are a couple of larger ones as well, so it's better to ask.}} * {{sleep | name=Hôtel Minerve | url=http://www.hotel-paris-minerve.com | email= | address=13, rue des Ecoles | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Maubert-Mutualité or Cardinal-Lemoine | phone=+33 1 43 26 26 04 | tollfree= | fax=+33 1 44 07 01 96 | hours= | price=€82-128 | checkin= | checkout= | content=While not quite the bargain it was a couple of years ago when it was (erroneously) classified as a two-star, the properly three-star Minerve is a family-run operation (the same family as the '''Familia''' next door. It's worth staying here just to enjoy the antique-stuffed lobby and the individual murals which adorn each of the rooms. The rooms are all air conditioned, and the bathtubs (if your room has one) are ''huge''. Watch your elbows in the tiny elevator though!}} * {{sleep | name=Hotel Parc Saint Severin | alt= | url=http://www.paris-hotel-parcsaintseverin.com/en/home/ | email= | address=22, rue de la Parcheminerie | lat= | long= | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | checkin= | checkout= | price= | content=On a pedestrian street away from the noise and only one minute from the heart of the quartier Latin and lively restaurants. }} * {{sleep | name=Maitre Albert B&B | alt= | url=http://www.private-homes.com {{dead link|June 2020|December 2020}} | email=contact@private-homes.com | address=rue Maitre Albert | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Maubert Mutualité or RER St Michel | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | checkin= | checkout= | price= €95 per night for two people including breakfast | content=This lovely bed & breakfast, facing a floral courtyard, is at the second floor of a grand old building in the historical part of Paris. At the end of Maître Albert's street are the river, the island and Notre Dame. }}
===Splurge=== * {{sleep | name=Hotel Mercure Paris La Sorbonne | alt= | url=https://all.accor.com/hotel/2897/index.en.shtml | email= | address=14, rue de la Sorbonne | lat= | long= | directions= | phone=+33 1 56 24 34 34 | tollfree= | checkin= | checkout= | price=€134+ | content=In the centre of Paris between the 5th and the 6th, in front of the Sorbonne, and one block from the Latin quarter and Saint Germain des Prés. Notre Dame is five minutes walking distance from the hotel. Fully renovated in a contemporary style, this hotel is very quiet and charming. }} * {{sleep | name=Hotel Notre Dame | alt= | url=http://www.hotelnotredameparis.com/index.html | email=info@hotelnotredameparis.com | address=1, quai Saint Michel | lat= | long= | directions= | phone=+33 1 43 54 20 43 | tollfree= | fax= | checkin= | checkout= | price=€140 | content=A modern hotel next to Notre Dame. Some rooms offer a view on the cathedral. Accommodations for 1 or 2, this hotel makes for a wonderful romantic getaway.}} * {{sleep | name=Hotel Les Rives De Notre Dame | url=http://paris-hotel-rivesnotredame.com/ | email=hotel@rivesdenotredame.com | address=15, quai Saint Michel | lat= | long= | directions= | phone=+33 1 43 54 81 16 | tollfree= | fax=+33 1 43262709 | hours= | price= | checkin= | checkout= | content=}}
==Connect==
==Go next== {{routebox | image1=Paris m 4 jms.svg | imagesize1=22 | directionl1=N | majorl1=[[Paris/1st arrondissement|1st arrondissement]] | minorl1=[[Paris/4th arrondissement|4th arrondissement]] | directionr1=S | majorr1=[[Paris/14th arrondissement|14th arrondissement]] | minorr1=[[Paris/6th arrondissement|6th arrondissement]] }}
{{guidedistrict}} {{geo|48.84513|2.35017|zoom=15}} {{IsPartOf|Paris}}

{{pagebanner | Jardin Luxembourg (Paris) banner.jpg|pgname=6th Arrondissement}} [[Image:Paris_6th_tower_st_germain_de_pres.jpg|thumb|240px|The 10th century church of Saint Germain de Pres]] As with [[Paris]] itself, the '''6th Arrondissement''' is hard to write about without using superlatives. There's a bit of everything here, from the busy sidewalks of Paris' main art Gallery scene to the expansive green spaces and under-tree cafés of the ''Jardin du Luxembourg'', from the impossible elegance and charm of the ''rue Bonaparte'' to the bohemian allure of the ''Latin Quarter'', from the huddle of 'steak/frites' joints around ''Place St. Michel'' to some of the finest restaurants in the world - the 6th has it all. Unsurprisingly, visitors find it one of the most romantic and appealing areas of Paris, but so do the Parisians themselves and for many years now the 6ème (as it is known in French) has been home to artists, writers, designers, intellectuals and the chicest of the chic. Unmissable though it may be, however, the charm of the 6th is such that you may risk not seeing much else of Paris!
==Get in== {{Mapframe|48.8488|2.3332|zoom=14}} {{Mapshape}} {{Mapshapes|Q50716}}
===By Métro=== {{rint|paris|4}} runs north-south through the 6th, connecting with the 18th, 9th, 2nd, 1st, and 14th. If you're arriving from central France or the Loire valley you'll probably connect at '''Gare Montparnasse'''.
===By RER=== {{rint|paris|rerB}} of the RER runs through {{station|Luxembourg}}, right next to the Luxembourg garden and close to the Panthéon.
===By bus=== Line 27, 89, 67, 83 run through
==See==
===Landmarks=== [[Image:Jardin du Luxembourg Paris France.JPG|thumb|Jardin du Luxembourg, the Luxembourg garden]] * {{see | name=Eglise Saint-Germain-des-Prés | alt=Abbey of Saint-Germain-des-Prés | url=http://www.eglise-sgp.org | email= | address=3 place St-Germain-des-Prés | lat=48.853889 | long=2.334444 | directions=Métro: St-Germain-des-Prés | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours=Daily 08:00-19:30 | price= | wikipedia=Abbey of Saint-Germain-des-Prés | image=Paris St-Germain-des-Prés.jpg | wikidata=Q334186 | content=The oldest church in Paris, founded in the year 542 by King Childebert. The church as it exists today dates mainly from the 11th century, the period in which it became the center of a powerful Benedictine abbey. The Revolution witnessed the suppression of the abbey in 1794, when most of the monastic buildings were put to the torch. Earlier, 318 priests had been hacked to death nearby by a mob on 3 September 1792. The church underwent significant restoration in the 19th century, ensuring the preservation of the building, which by that date represented a fascinating mix of styles: 6th century marble columns placed alongside Gothic vaults and supported by Romanesque arches. Famous burials within the church include René Descartes (philosopher), Nicolas Boileau (poet) and King John Casimir of Poland, who had become (in 1669, before his death) abbot of the church's monastery. }} * {{see | name=Palais du Luxembourg | alt= | url=http://www.senat.fr | email= | address=15 rue de Vaugirard | lat=48.848333 | long=2.3375 | directions=Métro Odéon or Mabillon | phone=+33 1 44 54 19 49 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=10:3-14:30 | price=free | wikipedia=Luxembourg Palace | image=Luxembourg Palace.JPG | wikidata=Q329852 |lastedit=2018-06-04| content=Visitable only by reservation and then only one Saturday every month. A richly decorated palace built for Marie de Medici in the early 17th century, which is now the French Senate. For those interested in seeing a Parisian monument normally unavailable to the public, or for those interested in the inner workings of the French Government. The large '''Luxembourg Garden''' is open to the public year-round. The garden is home to the Medici fountain, a children's playground, and vintage toy boats for hire that children push around in the Grand Bassin duck pond (a 90-year tradition). }} {{Multiple image |align=right |direction=vertical |width=170 |image1=Saint-Sulpice on 1739 Turgot map of Paris - KU.jpg |caption1=Saint Sulpice on the 1739 Turgot map of Paris |image2=P1000718 Paris VI Eglise Saint-Sulpice reductwk1.JPG |caption2=Façade of Saint Sulpice with balustrade and 'mis-matched' towers }} * {{see | name=Eglise de Saint Sulpice | alt= | url=http://pss75.fr/saint-sulpice-paris | email= | address=75 rue Bonaparte | lat=48.851111 | long=2.334722 | directions=Métro Saint Sulpice | phone=+33 1 42 34 59 98 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=07:00-18:45 | price=free | wikipedia=Church of Saint-Sulpice, Paris | image=P1000718 Paris VI Eglise Saint-Sulpice reductwk1.JPG | wikidata=Q295844 | content=a Roman Catholic church on the east side of the Place Saint-Sulpice within the rue Bonaparte, in the Luxembourg Quarter of the VIe arrondissement. At 113 metres long, 58 metres in width and 34 metres tall, it is only slightly smaller than Notre-Dame and thus the second largest church in the city. It is dedicated to Sulpitius the Pious. During the 18th century, an elaborate gnomon, the Gnomon of Saint-Sulpice, was constructed in the church. In front of the church itself is the magnificent Place Saint-Sulpice which contains the 'Fountain of the Four Bishops'. The church has a long-standing tradition of talented organists that dates back to the eighteenth century. In 1862, Aristide Cavaillé-Coll reconstructed and improved the existing organ built by François-Henri Clicquot. Though using many materials from Clicquot's French Classical organ, it is considered to be Cavaillé-Coll's magnum opus, featuring 102 speaking stops, and is perhaps the most impressive instrument of the romantic French symphonic-organ era. Its organists have also been renowned, starting with Nicolas Séjan in the 18th century, and continuing with Charles-Marie Widor (organist 1870-1933) and Marcel Dupré (organist 1934-1971), both great organists and composers of organ music. The current organists are 'titulaire' Daniel Roth (since 1985) and 'assistant titulaire' Sophie-Véronique Cauchefer-Choplin. In Saint-Sulpice Sunday organ recitals are held on a regular basis (Auditions du Dimanche, following the High Mass, usually from 11:30am till 12:05pm, during the subsequent mass, a visit of the organ loft is possible). }} *{{see | name=Monument to Balzac | alt= | url= | email= | address= | lat=48.8424221 | long=2.3294541 | directions=Boulevard Raspail/Boulevard du Montparnasse | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | wikipedia=Monument to Balzac | image=Monument to Balzac.jpg | wikidata=Q2770535 | content=A sculpture by Auguste Rodin in memory of the French novelist Honoré Balzac. The artwork is sometimes considered the first truly modern sculpture. }}
===Museums and galleries===
* {{see | name=Musée national Eugène Delacroix | alt= | url=http://www.musee-delacroix.fr | email= | address=6 rue de Fürstenberg | lat=48.8546 | long=2.3354 | directions=Métro: {{station|Mabillon|10}} or {{station|Saint-Germain-des-Près|4}} | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours=Tu-Su 09:30-17:00 (office closes 16:30), closed Christmas, New Year and 1 May | price=€5 discounts available, under-18s free | wikipedia=Musée national Eugène Delacroix | image=Musée national Eugène Delacroix Entrée.jpg | wikidata=Q1782606 | content=Home and studio of the great Romantic painter from 1857 until his death in 1863, features works by the artist and exhibitions of his contemporaries' work }}
==Do== *{{do | name=Cafe Philo in English | alt= | url=https://www.meetup.com/english-cafe-philo-in-paris/ | email= | address=Cafe de Flore, 172, Blvd St-Germain | lat=48.854088 | long=2.332649 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | hours= | price=Free | lastedit=2024-05-14 | content=Cafe Philo in English meets on the first Wednesday of each month upstairs at the famous [[#Q1025686|Café de Flore]]. Everyone is invited. You don't have to be knowledgeable about philosophy. Meetings begin with a two round voting process to determine a topic. The topic is discussed for two hours. }}
==Buy==
* {{buy | name=Citypharma Du Four Bonaparte | alt= | url=http://www.pharmacie-paris-citypharma.fr/ | email= | address=26 Rue de Four | lat=48.85271 | long=2.33341 | directions=Metro: St. Germain des Près | phone=+33 1 46 33 20 81 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=M-F 08:30-20:00, Sa 09:00-20:00 | price= | content=Cosmetic products of famous brands like "Avène", "Vichy" and "La Roche" can be bought cheaper here. }} * {{buy | name=La Chambre Claire | alt=La librairie de la photographie | url=http://www.la-chambre-claire.fr/ | email=libraire@la-chambre-claire.fr | address=14 rue Saint-Sulpice | lat=48.85152 | long=2.33726 | directions=Mabaillon, Odéon | phone=+33 1 46 34 04 31 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=M 14:00-19:00, Tu-Sa 12:00-19:00 | price= | content=The library is specialised on books about photography. They regularly organise book signings. }} * {{buy | name=Magasin Variantes | alt=Boutique Variantes | url=http://www.variantes.com/ | email= | address=29 rue Saint André des Arts | lat=48.85327 | long=2.34215 | directions=Odeon | phone=+33 1 43 26 01 01 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=M-Sa 10:30-20:00, Su 15:00-19:00 | price= | content=All kind of games are sold here, logic, go and check of course too. }} * {{buy | name=Malongo Café | alt= | url=http://www.malongo.com/ | email=st.andre@malongo.com | address=50 Rue Saint-André des Arts | lat=48.85344 | long=2.34060 | directions=Odéon | phone=+33 1 43 26 47 10 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=M-F 09:00-20:30, Su 10:00-19:00 | price= | content=Sells all kind of different Malongo café's. Next to the shop is a nice little bar to directly taste different ones. }} * {{buy | name=Marché bio Boulevard Raspail | alt= | url=http://equipement.paris.fr/marche-biologique-raspail-4515 {{dead link|June 2020|December 2020}} | email= | address= | lat=48.848953 | long=2.327570 | directions=Métro Rennes, entre les rues du Cherche-Midi et de Rennes | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours=Su 09:00-15:00 | price= | content=The market sells organic fruits and vegetables. }} * {{buy | name=Pâtisserie Sadaharu Aoki | alt= | url=http://www.sadaharuaoki.com/ | email= | address=35 rue de Vaugirard | lat=48.848017 | long=2.330415 | directions=Métro Rennes | phone=+33 1 45 44 48 90 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=Tu-Sa 11:00-19:00, Su 10:00-18:00 | price= | content=Japanese interpretation of French patisserie. }}
==Eat== [[Image:Paris_6th_sail_boat_rentals.jpg|thumb|180px|Rent a toy sail-boat in the Jardin du Luxembourg]]
===Budget=== The stretch of '''rue Vavin''' between rue Notre Dame and rue d'Assas (right before Jardin du Luxembourg) is filled with cheap eats that students frequent, such as a bakery with a dirt-cheap ''formule''. You can also find an outlet from the famous Amorino gelato chain here.
* {{eat | name=Guen Maï | url= | email= | address=6 Rue Cardinale | lat= | long= | directions= | phone=+33 1 43 26 03 24 | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | content=This macrobiotic vegetarian restaurant has a sheltered, quiet location and generally receives glowing reviews. }} * {{eat | name=Santa Lucia | url= | email= | address=22, Rue Canettes | lat= | long= | directions= | phone = +33 1 43 26 42 68 | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | content=Simple but very good Italian food. }} * {{eat | name=Cour de Rohan | url= | email= | address=59, Rue Saint André des Arts | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Saint-Michel | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | content=It would be an ordinary tea-room if the Cour de Rohan weren't such a magical little spot. }}
===Mid-range=== *{{eat | name=Kiwi Corner | url=http://www.kiwicorner.fr/ {{dead link|June 2020|December 2020}} | email= | address=25, rue Servandoni | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Odéon, Luxembourg | phone = +33 1-46-33-12-06 | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price=€20 | content=A little piece of New Zealand in the French capital. }} * {{eat | name=Padova | url=http://perso.wanadoo.fr/padova | email= | address=159 blvd. de Monparnasse | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: (RER-B) Port Royal | phone=+33 1 43 26 63 52 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=Tu-Sa 11:00-14:00 and 19:00-23:00 | price= | content=Good and ''big'' Italian food in this family-style restaurant. }} * {{eat | name=Yugaraj | url= | email= | address=14 Rue Dauphine | lat= | long= | directions=Metro: Pont-Neuf or Odeon | phone=+33 1 43 26 44 91 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=Around €40/person | price= | content=A mostly northern Indian ''carte'' with lots of '''Vegetarian''' options. It seems a popular restaurant so be sure to book in advance if you are going in a large group. }} * {{eat | name=l'Arbuci | url= | email= | address=25, rue de Buci | lat= | long= | directions= | phone=+33 1 44 32 16 00 | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | content=A nice bistro with consistently favorable reviews and a jazz club downstairs. }} * {{eat | name=Brasserie Lipp | alt= | url=https://www.brasserielipp.fr/en | email= | address=151, Bld. Saint-Germain | lat= | long= | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | hours= | price= | content=A Parisian institution since 1880, the beautiful art deco interior complements the famous Alsatian menu and blond beer. }} * {{eat | name=Le Timbre | url= | email= | address=3 rue Sainte Beuve | lat= | long= | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price=€33 | content=It's pretty much a two-person operation: chef Christopher Wright and a waitress. There is no ''carte'', so be prepared to have the menu. Reviewers who accept this prospect are universally unreserved in their praise. }} [[Image:Paris 6th arrondissement map with listings 2.png|thumb|350px|Map of the 6th Arrondissement]] * {{eat | name=Polidor | url= | email= | address=41, rue Monsieur Le Prince | lat= | long= | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | content=Since 1845, but don't let that fool you, the carte is quite up-to-date. Vegetarians can assemble a fine pasta-centered meal ''à la carte''. }}
===Splurge=== * {{eat | name=Ze Kitchen Gallery | url=http://www.zekitchengalerie.fr/ | email= | address=4 rue des Grands-Augustins | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Saint-Michel | phone=+33 1 44 32 00 32 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=M-F 12:00-14:30; M-Sa 19:00-23:00 | price=Main courses: €20-30 lunch menu with wine: ~€30 | content=A generally well-regarded fusion restaurant with another Guy Savoy trained chef. You should reserve if at all possible. }} * {{eat | name=Les Bouquinistes | url=http://www.guysavoy.com | email= | address=53 quai des Grands-Augustins | lat= | long= | directions= | phone=+33 1 43 25 45 94 | tollfree= | fax=+33 1 43 25 23 07 | hours= | price= | content=A favorite among the many art dealers in the neighborhood, and a respected platform for up-and-coming chef Magdala de Beaulieu-Caussimon. Owned by Guy Savoy. }}
==Drink==
===Cafés===
The 6th has two of Paris' most famous cafés, side by side - both are more expensive than your average café (you're paying for the history ''and'' the location, ''not'' for extraordinary fare or service):
* {{drink | name=Café de Flore | alt= | url=http://www.cafedeflore.fr/ | email= | address=172 boulevard Saint Germain | lat=48.853889 | long=2.3325 | directions=Métro: St-Germain-de-Prés | phone=+33 1 45 48 55 26 | tollfree= | hours=Daily 07:30-01:30 | price= | wikidata=Q1025686 | lastedit=2024-05-14 | content=This café is famous as the favored coffee and smoking venue for the Surrealists during the 1920s and '30s, the Existentialists in the 1940s and '50s, and still attracts an artistic and literary crowd. Also does breakfasts and light meals. }} * {{drink | name=Les Deux Magots | alt= | url=https://lesdeuxmagots.fr | email= | address=6 place Saint Germain de Prés | lat=48.853889 | long=2.333056 | directions=métro St Germain-des-Prés | phone=+33 1 45 48 55 25 | tollfree= | fax=+33 1 45 49 31 29 | hours=Daily 07:30-01:00 | price= | wikidata=Q1147912 | lastedit=2024-05-14 | content=Another famous literary café, right next door to its great rival Café de Flore. Sartre and Hemingway were regular patrons here and the café confirms its literary connections with an annual, somewhat prestigious book prize. }}
===Bars===
[[File:Bouquiniste sur les quais de la Seine (Paris, 2012).JPG|thumb|Booksellers on the quays of the Seine (2012)]] * {{drink | name=10 Bar International | url= | email= | address=10, rue de l'Odéon | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Odeon | phone=+33 1 43 26 66 83 | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price=A glass of wine will cost you about €3 | content=If you're looking to be lured into a classic Parisian hole-in-the-wall by the sound of accordion music, you should spend a few hours of your evening here. An artsy den with requisite nudie collage, their sangria is just right. }} * {{drink | name=The Moose | url= | email= | address=16, rue des Quatre Vents | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Odeon | phone=+33 1 46 33 77 00 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=M-F 16:00-02:00, Sa Su 11:00-02:00 | price=A glass of wine will cost you about €3.5, Happy Hour everyday 4-8 €5 a pint | content=One of the only sports bars in Paris, the Moose is a quirky anglophone refuge in the heart of the 6th district. Great to stop in for directions and a pint or to watch a game with some hearty North American food, and the mostly French crowd is usually up for speaking English ''or French'' with students and tourists. }}
==Sleep==
===Budget===
* {{sleep | name=Best Western Hotel Aramis in Saint Germain | url=http://www.hotelaramis.com/ | email=infos@hotelaramis.com | address=124, rue de Rennes | lat= | long= | directions=Metro: Right next to the Saint Placide underground station | phone =+33 1 45 48 03 75 | tollfree= | fax=+33 1 45 44 99 29 | hours= | price= | checkin= | checkout= | content=In a quiet street yet one of the liveliest neighbourhoods of Paris, the Hotel Aramis offers budget 3-star quality stays. }}
===Mid-range=== * {{sleep | name=Hotel Edouard VI *** | alt= | url=https://www.hotel-montparnasse-paris.com/en/ | email= | address= | lat= | long= | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | checkin= | checkout= | price= | wikipedia= | wikidata= | lastedit=2018-03-07 | content=A Montparnasse Hotel. Fully renovated, situated at the foot of the Montparnasse Tower and 50 m from the Montparnasse-Bienvenüe metro station. }} * {{sleep | name=Hotel Apostrophe | alt=Hôtel Poème | url=http://apostrophe-hotel.com/ | email=direction@apostrophe-hotel.com | address=3, rue de Chevreuse | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Vavin | phone=+33 1 56 54 31 31 | tollfree= | fax=+33 1 43 21 01 08 | checkin= | checkout= | price= | content=Set between Montparnasse and the Jardin du Luxembourg public park, near Saint-Germain-des-Prés, the Apostrophe hotel offers you an atmosphere full of poetry.16 guest rooms equipped with all the modern comfort, jet showers with light or "Chromo" jacuzzi-bath, audio CD & DVD player, complimentary Wi-Fi access.Each room has its own decor and invites you in a unique setting. Gay-friendly. }} * {{sleep | name=Hotel Le Saint Gregoire | url=http://www.hotelsaintgregoire.com | email=hotel@saintgregoire.com | address=43, rue de l'abbe Gregoire | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Saint Placide, between Saint-Germain des Prés and the Montparnasse district | phone =+33 1 45 48 23 23 | tollfree= | fax=+33 1 45 48 33 95 | hours= | price= | checkin= | checkout= | content=On a small, quiet street, the Hotel Le Saint-Gregoire has 20 rooms decorated by David Hicks with antique furnishings, paintings and lamps purchased by the owner. All rooms are air conditioned and equipped with Wi-Fi. }} * {{sleep | name=Le Clos Medicis | url=http://www.closmedicis.com | email=message@closmedicis.com | address=56 rue Monsieur-Le-Prince | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Odéon or Luxembourg | phone=+33 1 43 29 10 80 | tollfree= | fax=+33 1 43 54 26 90 | hours= | price=Rooms start at €120 | checkin= | checkout= | content=This charming little hotel is only steps from the ''Jardin du Luxembourg'' and has air-conditioning in every room, and a very cozy - and usually empty - bar in the lobby in which to wind down after a day of exploring, if you and your travelling companions need some quiet time. The helpful staff speaks English readily (some even as a first language), and the usual continental breakfast is served in the lovely (but tiny) courtyard every morning 07:00-11:00. }} * {{sleep | name=Hôtel Trianon Rive Gauche | url= | email= | address=1 bis et 3 rue de Vaugirard | lat= | long= | directions=Métro: Odeon, Cluny La Sorbonne, or RER-B: Luxembourg | phone=+33 1 55 33 16 55 | tollfree= | fax=+33 1 55 33 16 56 | hours= | price=rates from €120 | checkin= | checkout= | content=On the border between the 6th and the Latin Quarter in the 5th }} * {{sleep | name=K+K Hotel Cayré | url=http://www.kkhotels.com/en/hotels/paris/paris/overview-k-k-hotel-cayre/ | email=cayre@kkhotels.fr | address=4, Boulevard Raspail | lat= | long= | directions= | phone=+33 1 45 44 38 88 | tollfree= | fax=+33 1 45 44 98 13 | hours= | price= | checkin= | checkout= | content=Adjoining the Latin Quarter, the K+K Hotel Cayré hotel is within easy walking distance of the Louvre, Jardin des Tuileries and the Musee D'Orsay. }} * {{sleep | name=Hotel des Saints Pères | alt= | url=http://www.paris-hotel-saints-peres.com/en | email= | address= | lat= | long= | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | checkin= | checkout= | price= | content=Historical hotel with a typically left bank atmosphere, close to shops and cafés. }}
===Splurge=== [[File:Jardin du Luxembourg en été.jpg|thumb|Jardin du Luxembourg in summertime]] * {{sleep | name=Hôtel Au Manoir Saint Germain des Prés | url=http://www.paris-hotels-charm.com | email= | address=153 Boulevard Saint Germain | lat= | long= | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price=Rooms from €170 | checkin= | checkout= | content=In front of the Cafe de Flore and Aux Deux Magots offering guests a view over these two cafés and the Church of Saint Germain des Prés. Refurbished in 2008. }} * {{sleep | name=l'Hôtel | url= | email= | address=Rue des Beaux-Arts | lat= | long= | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price=Rooms from €300 | checkin= | checkout= | content=This hotel is beautiful inside, with baroque and modern rooms. There is a hamam style pool and sauna in the basement which can be reserved for clients of the hotel, and the restaurant is good too. Oscar Wilde lived and died here. }} *{{sleep | name=Milestay Saint-Germain | alt= | url=https://www.milestay.com/en/rentals/holidays-rentals-rentals-p0/tag-saint-germain/ {{dead link|December 2020}} | email=contact@milestay.com | address=117 rue de Rennes | lat=48.848081 | long=2.328198 | directions=Metro Rennes | phone=+33 140138580 | tollfree= | checkin=15:00 | checkout=11:00 | price=€350-750 | lastedit=2019-02-20 | content=3- & 4-bedroom furnished apartments for short stays. Available for groups (up to 8 people). Nice view on Eiffel Tower. }} * {{sleep | name=Victoria Palace Hotel | url=http://www.ila-chateau.com/victoria/ | email= | address=6, Rue Blaise Desgoffe | lat= | long= | directions=Metro: Saint Placide or Montparnasse | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price=Rooms start at €320 | checkin= | checkout= | content=An elegant hotel which has been a landmark on the Left Bank since 1913. The 62 rooms and suites combine lavish Louis XVI style and modern facilities. No restaurant but room service and buffet breakfast available. }}
==Connect==
==Go next== {{routebox | image1=Paris Metro 4.svg | imagesize1=22 | directionl1=N | majorl1=[[Paris/1st arrondissement|1st arrondissement]] | minorl1=[[Paris/5th arrondissement|5th arrondissement]] | directionr1=S | majorr1=[[Paris/14th arrondissement|14th arrondissement]] | minorr1= }}
{{geo|48.8488|2.3332|zoom=15}} {{IsPartOf|Paris}} {{usabledistrict}}

{{pagebanner | Paris 7e Wikivoyage banner.png|caption=7th arrondissement of Paris}}
The 7th arrondissement is perhaps the most expensive area to live in [[Paris]]. The Eiffel Tower, one of the most famous tourist sites in the world, is here, as well as many government buildings (ministries, the National Assembly and so on). Many dignitaries and VIPs populate this arrondissement.
[[Image:Eiffel_tower_panorama.jpg|thumb|right|Eiffel Tower panorama from the west]] ==Get in== {{Mapframe|48.85512|2.31176|zoom=14|width=520|height=370}} {{Mapshape}} {{Mapshapes|Q50716}}
=== By Métro/RER === *{{rint|paris|6}} serves '''Bir-Hakeim''' (Eiffel Tower). *{{rint|paris|8}} serves stations '''Invalides''' (Les Invalides), '''Varenne''' (Les Invalides, Musee de Rodin), '''Ecole-Militaire''' (Eiffel Tower), '''Latour Maubourg''' (Hotel des Invalides). *{{rint|paris|10}} serves '''Sèvres-Babylone''' (Le Bon Marche). *{{rint|paris|12}} serves stations '''Assemblée Nationale''', '''Solférino''', '''Rue du Bac''', '''Sèvres-Babylone'''. *{{rint|paris|13}} serves '''Invalides''' (Les Invalides). *RER {{rint|paris|rerC}} serves stations '''Invalides''' (Les Invalides), '''Champ de Mars-Tour Eiffel''' (Eiffel Tower), '''Musee D'Orsay''' (Musee D'Orsay).
=== By boat === * '''[http://www.batobus.com/english/index.htm Batobus]{{Dead link|date=January 2023 |bot=InternetArchiveBot }}''', the hop-on hop-off service serving tourist sites on the Seine has stops at Tour Eiffel and the Musée d'Orsay.
==See== [[Image:Paris 7th arrondissement map with listings 2.png|thumb|350px|Map of the 7th Arrondissement]]
===Landmarks=== {{Infobox|Eiffel Tower Light Show|From dusk till 02:00 there is a light show for ten minutes on the hour.}} * {{see | name=La Tour Eiffel | alt=The Eiffel Tower | url=http://www.toureiffel.paris/ | email= | address= | lat=48.8583 | long=2.2944 | directions={{station|Bir-Hakeim|6}} or {{station|École Militaire|8}}, {{station|Champ de Mars-Tour Eiffel|rerC}} | phone=+33 8 92 70 12 39 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=09:30-23:45; Jun 21-Sep 02: 09:00-00:45; Jul 14,Jul 15 off | price=€25 (€12 for age 12-24) to the top by lift. If you walk to the 2nd floor it is cheaper | wikipedia=Eiffel Tower | image=Tour_Eiffel_Wikimedia_Commons_(cropped).jpg | wikidata=Q243 | lastedit=2018-07-25 | content=A symbol of Paris and one of the most famous landmarks in the world. Built by Gustave Eiffel in 1887-1889, the tower was almost torn down in 1909 and only saved due to its use as a telegraphy antenna. The queues can be very long. The tower allows online reservations at its website. You can select a date and time frame. If you miss the time on your ticket, you have lost your money. The north, west, and east pillars have elevators that go to the first and second floors; the south pillar has stairs that can be climbed to the second floor. To reach the top floor, an additional elevator ride is required, and the wait for this can be very long as well. Disabled visitors are not allowed beyond the second floor due to safety concerns. Taking the Métro as far as Ecole Militiare and then strolling up the Champ de Mars is a lovely way to arrive at the tower. Another phenomenal approach is to exit the Metro at Trocadero and see the Eiffel Tower from the other side of the Ecole Militaire. }} * {{see | name=l'Assemblée Nationale | alt= | url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/ | email= | address=33, quai d'Orsay | lat=48.862192 | long=2.318716 | directions= | phone=+33 1 40 63 60 00 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=M F Sa 08:40-11:40 and 14:00-17:00 | price= | wikipedia=National Assembly (France) | image=Paris Assemblee Nationale DSC00074.jpg | wikidata=Q193582 | content=Guided tours conducted all day, ID required. Formerly the Palais Bourbon, this building has housed the National Assembly, the French parliament's lower house, since 1827. Some interesting architecture and the library features the painting ''l'Histoire de la civilization'' by Delacroix. Visitors may be interested in attending assembly debates. }} * {{see | name=Hôtel des Invalides | alt= | url=https://www.musee-armee.fr/en/your-visit/museum-spaces/national-hotel-of-the-invalids.html | email= | address=6, boul des Invalides | lat=48.855 | long=2.3125 | directions={{station|Varenne|13}} or {{station|Invalides|8|13|rerC}} | phone= | tollfree= | hours= | price= | wikipedia=Les Invalides | image=Hôtel des Invalides - 20150801 16h09 (10630).jpg | wikidata=Q188977 | content=Founded in 1671 by Louis XIV as a hospital for 6,000 wounded soldiers—this function explaining the name of the building—the golden-domed Hôtel des Invalides still functions as an infirmary and now also houses the ''Musée de l'Armée''. The church attached, ''l'Eglise du Dôme'', houses the tomb of Napoleon. }}
===Museums and Galleries=== [[File:Cour intérieure des Invalides1.jpg|thumb|250px|The Musée de l'Armée is housed in the Invalides complex]]
* {{see | name=Musée de l'Armée | alt= | url=http://www.musee-armee.fr/en/english-version.html | email= | address=129, rue de Grenelle | lat=48.85694444 | long=2.31277778 | directions={{station|Latour-Maubourg}}, {{station|Invalides}}, {{station|Saint-François-Xavier}} | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours=10:00-17:00 (1 Oct-31 Mar), 10:00-18:00 (1 Apr-30 Sep), closed on the first M of each month | price=Admission €9, with discount €7 | wikipedia=Musée de l'Armée | image=ShimonosekiCannon.jpg | wikidata=Q1996069 | content=This museum is in the historic Invalides complex and presents the history of the French Army. It is co-located with Napoleon Bonaparte's tomb (entry to which is included in the ticket price). Most of the exhibitions are very old fashioned, and the coverage of the First World War is surprisingly limited. A highlight is the Musée des Plans-Reliefs, which displays painstakingly accurate models of French fortresses and includes its own shop. }} * {{see | name=Musée d'Orsay | alt= | url=http://www.musee-orsay.fr/ | email= | address=1, rue de la Légion d'Honneur / rue de Lille | lat=48.86 | long=2.326389 | directions=On the Left Bank of the Seine, adjacent to the Pont Solferino and Pont Royal, opposite the Jardin des Tuileries, {{station|Musée d'Orsay|rerC}} or {{station|Solférino|12}}, bus 24, 63, 68, 69, 73, 83, 84, 94 | phone=+33 1 06 91 09 45 | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price=€9; concessions €6.50; under 18 or 26 for EU member states free | wikipedia=Musée d'Orsay | image=MuseeOrsay 20070324.jpg | wikidata=Q23402 | content=Housed in a former ''Beaux-Arts'' railway station (completed in 1900 for the ''Exposition Universelle'', later saved from demolition and converted to its present use), the rambling, open-plan museum is home to the works of the great artists of the 19th century (1848-1914) - Impressionists, post-Impressionists, and the rest - that were formerly displayed in the l'Orangerie. This is perhaps the most spectacular collection of European impressionism in the world—breath-taking rooms full of Manet, Renoir, Monet, Van Gogh, and many others. Impressionist represent the biggest draw, but there is much more to explore. }} * {{see | name=Musée du quai Branly | alt= | url=http://www.quaibranly.fr | email= | address=37, quai Branly | lat=48.86098 | long=2.29787 | directions={{station|Iéna}}, {{station|Bir Hakeim}} | phone= | tollfree= | hours=Open Tu-Su 10:30-19:00 (Th til 21:00). | price=Admission €14.00 | wikipedia=Musée du quai Branly | image=Musée du quai Branly P1020787.JPG | wikidata=Q167863 | lastedit=2025-10-13 | content=Opened in 2006, this is the newest and the most modern of Paris' great museums, housing an outstanding collection of tribal art, with a particular emphasis on France's former (and present) territories in Oceania and Africa. The museum is large and you can easily spend half a day browsing, especially if you pause to explore the multimedia presentations. }} * {{see | name=Musée Rodin | alt= | url=http://www.musee-rodin.fr/ | email= | address=79, rue de Varenne | lat=48.855356 | long=2.315819 | directions=Metro: {{station|Varenne|13}}; RER: {{station|Invalides}} | phone=+33 1 44 18 61 10 | tollfree= | fax=+33 1 44 18 61 30 | hours=Tu-Su: museum: 10:00-17:45, park: till 18:00; ticket office: till 17:15. Closed M | price=Admission €5, with discount €3, garden only €1, family ticket €10 (2 adults+1 child, museum+garden), visitors under 18 free | wikipedia=Musée Rodin | image=Musee Rodin.jpg | wikidata=Q650519 | content=A museum dedicated to the life and work of the great sculptor. The house contains an extensive collection, which is unusually well presented in a spacious building with big windows that are open in nice weather, which makes this museum double pleasant. }}
===Other attractions===
* {{see | name=Musée des Égouts de Paris | alt=Paris Sewer Museum | url=https://en.parisinfo.com/paris-museum-monument/71499/Musee-des-egouts-de-Paris | email= | address= | lat=48.862611 | long=2.302528 | directions=Entrance opposite 93, quai d'Orsay near the Pont d'Alma, {{station|Alma-Marceau}} | phone=+33 1 53 68 27 81 | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price=Full fare: €4.30, Student: €3.50 | wikipedia=Paris Sewer Museum | image=Musee des Egouts de Paris FRA 002.JPG | wikidata=Q2654419 | content=For an interesting take on Paris, check out the underground sewers of Paris. See swords found in the sewers over the years and get an appreciation for what it takes to keep Paris running. }}
