{{pagebanner|La-Défense banner Skyline.jpg|pgname=La Défense}} '''La Défense''' is a collection of modern high-rise office and residential buildings built according to an evolving central plan on the western outskirts of [[Paris]], beyond the last Parisian loop of the river Seine. La Défense is the site of the Grande Arche, one of Paris' most modern and imposing landmarks, situated at the western end of the grand axis formed by the ''Champs-Elysées'', the ''Place de la Concorde'' and the ''Arc de Triomphe''.
La Défense makes up the western end of the [[Axe historique]], a route of monumental buildings extending to the Louvre and the Bastille.
== Understand == La Défense is a purpose-built business district; in the 1960s, Charles de Gaulle led an effort to level the area and concentrate skyscrapers in a single business district, rather than altering the character of Paris with large commercial buildings. Despite being officially and popularly recognised, and invariably associated with Paris, La Défense is neither an official administrative unit nor is it within Paris' city limits. The area of La Défense is actually on the borders of three communes of the Hauts-de-Seine department beyond the borders of Paris proper - '''Nanterre''', '''Courbevoie''' and '''Puteaux'''.
==Get in== La Défense is the most important office region in Paris region. This means it is well connected to the rest of the Paris region.
===By métro=== *''La Défense'' (ligne 1, RER lines A and E) *''Esplanade de la Défense'' (ligne 1)
===By train and tram=== La Défense can be reached on RER A and E, Transilien L, Transilien U, Tramway T2, which all stop at the eponymous La Défense station. The RER A, E and Transilien stations are in zone 3 and therefore cannot be accessed with a T+ ticket.
The station layout can be very confusing but ''Les Quatres Temps'' shopping centre is colour-coded.
==See== {{Mapframe|48.89226|2.24018|zoom=14}} {{Mapshape|wikidata=Q22249037}} {{mapshapes|Q1142114|stroke-width=2}} <!-- Tram --> {{Mapshapes|Q50716}} {{mapshapes|Q389554}} <!-- Transilien --> {{mapshapes|Q216125}} <!-- RER (put here so that it is drawn over Transilien) -->
[[File:La Defense and Champs Elysees.JPG|thumb|La Défense seen from Arc de Triomphe]] === In La Défense === * {{see | name=Grande Arche de la Defense | alt= | url=https://www.grandearche.com/grande-arche-monument-majeur-de-defense-de-paris/ | email= | address=1 Le Parvis de La Défense | lat=48.892778 | long=2.235833 | directions={{station|La Défense|1|rerA}} | phone=+33 1 49 07 27 27 | tollfree= | hours=10:00-19:00 | price= | wikipedia=Grande Arche | image=Paris - Blick vom großen Triumphbogen.jpg | wikidata=Q216357 | content=A high-rise building that looks more like a hollow cube than an actual arch. The viewing platform on its top closed due to a 2010 elevator incident, reopened in May 2017, and is open as of October 2025 after another closure.. }} * {{see | name=Centre des nouvelles industries et technologies | alt=CNIT | url= | email= | address= | lat=48.892778 | long=2.239472 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | hours= | price= | wikipedia=Center of New Industries and Technologies | wikidata=Q431326 | lastedit=2025-10-22 | content=The largest unsupported concrete span enclosed space in the world. Houses shops and offices, ESSEC Business School campus and a Hilton hotel. }} * {{see | name=Musée de La Défense| alt= | url= | email=communication@defacto.fr | address=15, place de La Défense | lat=48.89077 | long=2.24230 | directions= | phone=+33 1 47 74 84 24 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=Su-F 09:00-17:00, Sa 10:00-18:00 | price= | content=The museum presents the history of the development of La Défense, with many plans and scale models. }}
==== Architecture ==== Each of the buildings of La Défense tells a story of architectural trends that were ''en vogue'' at the times of its construction and design. A tour of La Défense can be a quick overview through the most recent period in the history of architecture * {{see | name=Notre-Dame de Pentecôte | alt= | url=https://ndp92.fr/ | email= | address= | lat=48.8919 | long=2.24097 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | hours= | price= | image=Notre Dame de Pentecote.jpg | wikidata=Q3344684 | lastedit=2025-10-22 | content=This unusual church building was erected in 2001 and designed by Franck Hammoutène. }}
==== Art ==== There are over 60 works of art displayed in the open air throughout La Défense, interspersed within public spaces and freely accessible, and authored by some of the biggest names in modern art. * ''Le pouce'', a giant statue of a thumb by César Baldaccini, stands between the CNIT and the Grande Arche * The abstract ''Spider'' by Alexander Calder simply cannot be missed on the Esplanade * The ''Bright Trees'' by Vassilakis Takis visually enclose the Esplanade
=== Beyond La Défense === * {{see | name=Forteresse du Mont-Valérien | alt= | url=http://www.mont-valerien.fr | email= | address= | lat=48.872828 | long=2.213313 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | hours= | price= | wikidata=Q16928476 | lastedit=2025-10-22 | content= }} ==== Nanterre ==== * {{see | name=Tours Aillaud | alt= | url= | email= | address= | lat=48.889489 | long=2.227392 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | wikipedia=Tours Aillaud | image=Tours Aillaud, de la prefecture des Hauts de Seine.JPG | wikidata=Q1476044 | content=South-west from the Grande Arche you can find these tall cylindrical concrete residential towers, painted in various colours. Representing a 1970s urbanistic experiment, the 18 towers remain controversial and unique, and continue to house thousands of inhabitants in over 1600 apartments. }} * {{see | name=Parc André Malraux | alt= | url= | email= | address= | lat=48.892412 | long=2.219726 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | hours= | price= | wikidata=Q61082449 | lastedit=2025-10-22 | content=The expansive, calm park around a lake extends westwards behind the Tours Aillaud, and is to La Défense what Central Park is to Downtown Manhattan. You can take spectacular pictures of the skyline juxtaposed against the park's greenery from there. }} * {{see | name=Nanterre Cathedral | alt=Église Notre Dame de Pitié | url= | email= | address=28 Rue de l'Église | lat=48.890833 | long=2.196111 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | wikipedia=Nanterre Cathedral | image=Cathédrale de Nanterre01.jpg | wikidata=Q2942477 | content=Built in the 1920s, it is no match for the Notre Dame de Paris in either historical importance or architectural detailing, but it can be an interesting destination for those interested in sacral architecture. }} * {{see | name=Paris La Défense Arena | alt= | url=https://www.parisladefense-arena.com | email= | address=99 Jardin de l'Arche | lat=48.895844 | long=2.230203 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | hours= | price= | wikipedia=Paris La Défense Arena | wikidata=Q2860806 | lastedit=2025-10-22 | content=A domed stadium near the Grande Arche. It opened in October 2017, and its main tenant is the rugby union club Racing 92. The facility can host everything from court sports to concerts, with configurations ranging from 10,000 for court sports, 32,000 for rugby, and 40,000 for concerts. It hosted gymnastics events during the 2024 Summer Olympics }}
==== Courbevoie ==== * {{see | name=Pavillon des Indes | alt= | url= | email= | address= | lat=48.8996 | long=2.26811 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | image=Pavillon des indes coté sud.JPG | wikidata=Q13518147 | content=The wooden Indian pavilion was moved from Paris to Courbevoie following the Universal Exhibition of 1878, and remains a curiosity amidst the much more modern architecture of the commune. }} ==== Puteaux ==== * {{see | name=Théâtre des Hauts-de-Seine | alt= | url= | email= | address= | lat=48.88048 | long=2.24072 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | content=A 19th-century theatre building. }}
